aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.01977418-caee-4eb3-9a56-a8437ab43124.prompt=Password\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.094fda41-eb53-4324-9fb3-2c88ba297530.prompt=Enter Host\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.0e56704b-ecab-4f00-a206-8cd4e842d14d.description=
Retrieves detailed information about a specific device configuration.

Inputs\:
    coreHost - The DNS name or IP Address of your NAS core.
    corePort - The port used to connect to your NAS core.
Default value\: 443
    coreProtocol - The protocol used to connect to your NAS core.
Default value\: https
Valid values\: http, https
    coreUsername - The username for the NAS core.
    corePassword - The password for the NAS user.
    id - The configuration's ID for which the details are retrieved.

Results\:
    returnResult - Device configuration (or snapshot) details.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.


Notes\:
1. The configuration's ID can be obtained using the operation "Get Configurations By IP".
2. This operation effectively returns the Device Configuration Detail Page, in text format, which enables you to examine the details of a specific configuration.
aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.0e66ac79-eb87-4503-a053-abaf1b3ff7ca.prompt=Login\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.10ca36fb-5e0f-446b-9d5c-e7e4ab1d2c8b.description=This flow is used to Update Incidents. Inputs host - The URL of the ServiceNow instance. Format\: scheme\://domain Example\: https\://dev10000.service-now.com authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server. The authentication is not preemptive\: a plain request not including authentication info will be made and only when the server responds with a 'WWW-Authenticate' header the client will send required headers. If the server needs no authentication but you specify one in this input the request will work nevertheless. The client cannot choose the authentication method and there is no fallback so you have to know which one you need. If the web application and proxy use different authentication types, these must be specified like in the Example model. Default value\: basic Valid values\: basic, digest, ntlm, kerberos, any, anonymous, "" or a list of valid values separated by comma. Example\: basic | basic,digest username - The ServiceNow username used to perform the request. password - The ServiceNow password used to perform the request. apiVersion - The API version with which the request will be sent. The call will be made using the latest API version when this input is left empty. Example\: v1 systemId - The System ID of the of the Incident to be updated. Example\: 71c7ac460f811200ff7eb17ce1050e7a requestBody - The string to include in the body of the request, in the format accepted by ServiceNow. In case more Incident fields need to be addressed, they can be provided in the "requestBody" input. When a custom body is provided, the values provided in the inputs named "incident" will be ignored unless their reference is used in the new body. Example\: {'short_description'\:'Example description','severity'\:'1','assigned_to'\:'46c1293aa9fe1981000dc753e75ebeee','state'\:'4'} incidentShortDescription - The short description of the Incident to be created, in the form of a string. If this input is left empty, the short description of the created Incident will be empty. incidentNumber - The number of the Incident to be created. Should contain the "INC" prefix followed by 7 or more digits. If this input is left empty, ServiceNow will automatically assign a number. Example\: INC0100001 incidentCaller - The system ID of the Caller. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 incidentLocation - The system ID of the Location. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 incidentCategory - The Category name in the form of a string. Example\: Software, Inquiry / Help incidentSubcategory - The Subcategory name in the form of a string. Example\: Email, Operating System incidentImpact - The Impact of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 3. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3 incidentUrgency - The Urgency of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 3. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3 incidentPriority - The Priority of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 5. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 incidentOpenedBy - The system ID of the entity that submitted the Incident. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 incidentContactType - The Contact Type in the form of a string. Example\: Phone, Email incidentState - The State of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 7. Each integer represents an Incident State as follows\: 1\=New, 2\=Active, 3\=Awaiting Problem, 4\=Awaiting User Info, 5\=Awaiting Evidence, 6\=Resolved, 7\=Closed. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7 incidentAssignmentGroup - The system ID of the Assignment Group. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 incidentAssignedTo - The system ID of the entity to which the Incident should be assigned to. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 preemptiveAuth - If this field is "true", authentication info will be sent in the first request. If this is "false" a request with no authentication info will be made and if the server responds with 401 and a header such as WWW-Authenticate\: Basic realm\="myRealm", only then will the authentication info be sent. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the web site. proxyPort - The proxy server port. Default value\: 8080. Valid values\: -1, and positive integer values. When the value is '-1' the default port of the scheme, specified in the 'proxyHost', will be used. proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy. proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value. trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL/TSL. A certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it. Default value\: false Valid values\: true, false x509HostnameVerifier - Specifies the way the server hostname must match a domain name in the subject's Common Name (CN) or subjectAltName field of the X.509 certificate. The hostname verification system prevents communication with other hosts other than the ones you intended. This is done by checking that the hostname is in the subject alternative name extension of the certificate. This system is designed to ensure that, if an attacker (Man-In-The-Middle) redirects traffic to his machine, the client will not accept the connection. If you set this input to "allow_all", this verification is ignored and you become vulnerable to security attacks. For the value "browser_compatible" the hostname verifier works the same way as Curl and Firefox. The hostname must match either the first CN, or any of the subject-alts. A wildcard can occur in the CN, and in any of the subject-alts. The only difference between "browser_compatible" and "strict" is that a wildcard (such as "*.foo.com") with "browser_compatible" matches all subdomains, including "a.b.foo.com". From the security perspective, to provide protection against possible Man-In-The-Middle attacks, we strongly recommend to use "strict" option. Default value\: strict Valid values\: strict, browser_compatible, allow_all trustKeystore - The pathname of the Java TrustStore file. This contains certificates from other parties that you expect to communicate with, or from Certificate Authorities that you trust to identify other parties. If the protocol (specified by the URL) is not HTTPS or if trustAllRoots is "true" this input is ignored. Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts Format\: Java KeyStore (JKS) trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file. If trustAllRoots is false and trustKeystore is empty, trustPassword default will be supplied. Default value\: changeit connectTimeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A timeout value of 0 represents an infinite timeout. Default value\: 0 Format\: an integer representing seconds Examples\: 10, 20 socketTimeout - The timeout for waiting for data (a maximum period inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A socketTimeout value of 0 represents an infinite timeout. Default value\: 0 Format\: an integer representing seconds useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls in a serializable session object therefore they will be available on a branch level (same subflow, same lane). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false keepAlive - Specifies whether to create a shared connection that will be used in subsequent calls. If keepAlive is false, the already open connection will be used and after execution it will close it. The operation will use a connection pool stored in a GlobalSessionObject that will be available throughout the execution (the flow and subflows, between parallel split lanes). Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false connectionsMaxPerRoute - The maximum limit of connections on a per route basis. The default will create no more than 2 concurrent connections per given route. Default value\: 2 connectionsMaxTotal - The maximum limit of connections in total. The default will create no more than 2 concurrent connections in total. Default value\: 20 headers - The list containing the headers to use for the request separated by new line (CRLF).The header name - value pair will be separated by "\:". Format\: According to HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616). Examples\: Accept\:text/plain responseCharacterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP response. If responseCharacterSet is empty, the charset from the 'Content-Type' HTTP response header will be used. If responseCharacterSet is empty and the charset from the HTTP response Content-Type header is empty, the default value will be used. You should not use this for method\=HEAD or OPTIONS. Default value\: ISO-8859-1 followRedirects - Specifies whether the HTTP client automatically follows redirects. Redirects explicitly prohibited by the HTTP specification as requiring user intervention will not be followed (redirects on POST and PUT requests that are converted to GET requests). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false requestCharacterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP request body. If contentType is empty, the requestCharacterSet will use the default value. If contentType will include charset (ex.\: "application/json; charset\=UTF-8"), the requestCharacterSet value will overwrite the charset value from contentType input. This should not be provided for method\=GET, HEAD, TRACE Default value\: ISO-8859-1 Results\: returnResult - This will contain the response entity. In case of an error this output will contain the error message. document - This will contain the response body. exception - In case of success response, this result is empty. In case of failure response, this result contains the java stack trace of the runtime exception. statusCode - The HTTP status code. Format\: 1xx (Informational - Request received, continuing process), 2xx (Success - The action was successfully received, understood, and accepted), 3xx (Redirection - Further action must be taken in order to complete the request), 4xx (Client Error - The request contains bad syntax or cannot be fulfilled), 5xx Server Error - The server failed to fulfil an apparently valid request) Examples\: 200, 404 responseHeaders - The list containing the headers of the response message, separated by newline. Format\: This is conforming with HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616). Responses success - The operation completed without a runtime exception. failure - A runtime exception occurred. This may be due to incorrectly formated inputs (headers, proxy, queryParams, url). Notes\: 1. The values stored in the fields of the Incident will not be changed if the "incident" inputs are left empty. 2. The reference of the "incident" inputs should be removed from inside the "requestBody" input when they are deleted. 3. When more Incident fields are required, than the ones exposed, you can add them as inputs and insert their reference in the Json found in the "requestBody" input. 4. In order to authenticate using an OAuth token\: 4.1. The headers input should contain the following header\: Authorization\:Bearer 4.2. The username and password inputs should remain empty. aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.1604896f-fab2-45c4-a4c8-7f646d942155.prompt=Protocol\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.1ad3ffaa-1cae-4183-a885-6d9d0d6385a8.description=
Executes a NA command via the command line SSH interface

Inputs\:
hostname - NA host
username - NA user
password - user password
Command - NA command to execute
sessionId - identifier of a shared SSH shell session created by SSH Shell Logon. instead of creating a new SSH shell session this one will be used if populated.
port - the port number for running the command. It overwrites the port given inside the host input -in a syntax like host\:port-, if this exists.

Responses\:
success - successfully executed the command
failure - failed to execute the command or non-200 code response received

Returns\:
cmdResult - the result of the NA command

This operator determines whether or not a given ping and packet loss are below a set of specified thresholds.

Inputs\:
percentLoss - The measured % loss.
lossThreshold - The maximum % loss that is acceptable.
averageLatency - The milliseconds of latency measured.
latencyThreshold - The maximum milliseconds of latency that is acceptable.

Responses\:
connection passed - both percentLoss and averageLatency were below thresholds.
no response - There was 100% packet loss.
packet loss too high - percentLoss was greater than lossThreshold.
average latency too high - averageLatency was greater than latencyThreshold.
aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.4f7077a4-aa8a-4ae1-9d5f-15361b87a5dc.description=
Runs a diagnostic task against a device or device group.

Inputs\:
coreHost - The DNS name or IP Address of your NAS core.
corePort - The port to connect to your NAS core on.
coreProtocol - The protocol to connect to your NAS core with. Either HTTP or HTTPS.
coreUsername - The username for the NAS core.
corePassword - The password for the NAS user.
diagnosticName - A diagnostic to run. For example,  "NA Routing Table", "NA Interfaces" and "NA OSPF Neighbors'" etc. See the "NA Diagnostics" selection list and its description for detail. If integrate with Network Automation whose version is older than 7.50, change the default selection list to "NAS Diagnostics" selection list. 
ip - The IP address of the network device.
groupName - The group name of a list of networked devices.
comment - The comment to tie to this action.
repeat - (\#min | \#\:\# | \#days | \#weeks | \#months) where \# is a positive integer. \#\:\# is hours\:minutes--the two integers do not have to be the same.
startDate - Date of the start of the task. May be in one of the following formats\:  YYYY\:MM\:DD\:HH\:MM e.g. 2002\:09\:06\:12\:30, now or tomorrow.
returnImmediately - A boolean value. If true (1), the operation will return once the task is scheduled. If false (0) the operation will wait for the task to complete before returning.

Responses\:
success - The operation completed successfully.
failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
returnResult - Text result of NAS diagnostic

Extra Results\:
commandStatus - The status of the NAS command.
text - The response text of the NAS command.
stackTrace - The stack trace (If any) of the NAS command.
aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.52a59621-d491-4900-b99d-dc480250a2f0.prompt=NA Command\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.54ce2a6f-8960-40fe-9989-68d3a85cea00.prompt=Enter Host\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.597aa4c3-bffe-43e9-9785-0fde0931e119.prompt=NA Command\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.5a582e3e-54bb-48b4-b35b-9f021ca2ee29.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex (The values are not case sensitive)
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.695f738f-790f-47ae-98b2-d5ba6fc60b0a.prompt=Username\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.6d09d78b-9207-4438-a96a-62c6f9959b2d.prompt=Password\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.7d465576-7ad0-41b3-bcc7-849cbe2c81be.prompt=Configuration ID\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.7d4a6f68-f7cb-41be-bcb9-7e804de617e1.prompt=Target host name\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.8818c5fa-ac38-4538-aff2-34030a8cbb08.prompt=Password\: aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.93093fd6-cb08-4a23-ac58-68806ad83c61.description=
Runs a Ping command either locally or remotely depending on the specified protocol. Credentials and other inputs (remoteOS, hostname, username, password, keyFile etc) are required if the command must be run from a remote host. The Telnet protocol also requires inputs for usernamePrompt and passwordPrompt. 

Inputs\:
    hostname - Hostname or IP address of the host computer where the Ping command will be executed.
    username - A username to authenticate to the host computer. 
    password - The password for the user account.
    targetHost - Hostname or IP address of the target host computer.
    protocol  - The protocol used to run the command.
Values\: local, ssh, Telnet
    packetSize - The size of the ping packet.
    packetCount - The number of ping packets to send.
    remoteOS - The operating system of the host computer (WINDOWS, LINUX, SOLARIS only are supported), if Ping is running on a remote host.
    usernamePrompt - The username prompt seen while using Telnet protocol. This input is required when Telnet protocol is used. For example, login\:.
    passwordPrompt - The password prompt seen while using Telnet protocol. This input is required when Telnet protocol is used. For example, password\:.
    keyFile - The path to the private key file for remote host. The path should be absolute.
    timeout - The timeout in miliseconds for the Ping operation. Default is 90000.-A inet6
    ipVersion - IP version forced to the ping command executed on the target host. For Windows -4 or -6 parameters will be added.On Linux will be used ping or ping6. For Solaris -A inet or -A inet6 parameters will be added. For empty string the operation will decide what format to use if targetHost is an ip literal; if targetHost is given as a hostname default 'ping' command will be used on each operating system.
Values\: 4, 6, '' (empty string without quotes).
Default\: '' (empty string without quotes).

Responses\:
    success - The command executed successfully.
    failure - The command could not be executed or had a problem during execution.

Returns\:
    packetsSent - The number of packets sent.
    packetsReceived - The number of packets received.
    percentagePacketsLost - The percentage of packets lost.
    transmissionTimeMin - Minimum time taken for transmitting the packet.
    transmissionTimeMax - Maximum time taken for transmitting the packet.
    transmissionTimeAvg - Average time taken for transmitting the packet.
    returnResult - Raw output of the command.
    returnCode - Return code of the executed command.
    error - The STDERR of the command.

This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex (The values are not case sensitive)
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

aec2a220-d36b-4350-a97f-4937abfe6d99.e046f286-309b-421e-a92a-e7038f5ab1de.description=This flow is used to Update Incidents. Inputs host - The URL of the ServiceNow instance. Format\: scheme\://domain Example\: https\://dev10000.service-now.com authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server. The authentication is not preemptive\: a plain request not including authentication info will be made and only when the server responds with a 'WWW-Authenticate' header the client will send required headers. If the server needs no authentication but you specify one in this input the request will work nevertheless. The client cannot choose the authentication method and there is no fallback so you have to know which one you need. If the web application and proxy use different authentication types, these must be specified like in the Example model. Default value\: basic Valid values\: basic, digest, ntlm, kerberos, any, anonymous, "" or a list of valid values separated by comma. Example\: basic | basic,digest username - The ServiceNow username used to perform the request. password - The ServiceNow password used to perform the request. apiVersion - The API version with which the request will be sent. The call will be made using the latest API version when this input is left empty. Example\: v1 systemId - The System ID of the of the Incident to be updated. Example\: 71c7ac460f811200ff7eb17ce1050e7a requestBody - The string to include in the body of the request, in the format accepted by ServiceNow. In case more Incident fields need to be addressed, they can be provided in the "requestBody" input. When a custom body is provided, the values provided in the inputs named "incident" will be ignored unless their reference is used in the new body. Example\: {'short_description'\:'Example description','severity'\:'1','assigned_to'\:'46c1293aa9fe1981000dc753e75ebeee','state'\:'4'} incidentShortDescription - The short description of the Incident to be created, in the form of a string. If this input is left empty, the short description of the created Incident will be empty. incidentNumber - The number of the Incident to be created. Should contain the "INC" prefix followed by 7 or more digits. If this input is left empty, ServiceNow will automatically assign a number. Example\: INC0100001 incidentCaller - The system ID of the Caller. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 incidentLocation - The system ID of the Location. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 incidentCategory - The Category name in the form of a string. Example\: Software, Inquiry / Help incidentSubcategory - The Subcategory name in the form of a string. Example\: Email, Operating System incidentImpact - The Impact of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 3. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3 incidentUrgency - The Urgency of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 3. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3 incidentPriority - The Priority of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 5. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 incidentOpenedBy - The system ID of the entity that submitted the Incident. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 incidentContactType - The Contact Type in the form of a string. Example\: Phone, Email incidentState - The State of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 7. Each integer represents an Incident State as follows\: 1\=New, 2\=Active, 3\=Awaiting Problem, 4\=Awaiting User Info, 5\=Awaiting Evidence, 6\=Resolved, 7\=Closed. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7 incidentAssignmentGroup - The system ID of the Assignment Group. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 incidentAssignedTo - The system ID of the entity to which the Incident should be assigned to. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 preemptiveAuth - If this field is "true", authentication info will be sent in the first request. If this is "false" a request with no authentication info will be made and if the server responds with 401 and a header such as WWW-Authenticate\: Basic realm\="myRealm", only then will the authentication info be sent. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the web site. proxyPort - The proxy server port. Default value\: 8080. Valid values\: -1, and positive integer values. When the value is '-1' the default port of the scheme, specified in the 'proxyHost', will be used. proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy. proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value. trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL/TSL. A certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it. Default value\: false Valid values\: true, false x509HostnameVerifier - Specifies the way the server hostname must match a domain name in the subject's Common Name (CN) or subjectAltName field of the X.509 certificate. The hostname verification system prevents communication with other hosts other than the ones you intended. This is done by checking that the hostname is in the subject alternative name extension of the certificate. This system is designed to ensure that, if an attacker (Man-In-The-Middle) redirects traffic to his machine, the client will not accept the connection. If you set this input to "allow_all", this verification is ignored and you become vulnerable to security attacks. For the value "browser_compatible" the hostname verifier works the same way as Curl and Firefox. The hostname must match either the first CN, or any of the subject-alts. A wildcard can occur in the CN, and in any of the subject-alts. The only difference between "browser_compatible" and "strict" is that a wildcard (such as "*.foo.com") with "browser_compatible" matches all subdomains, including "a.b.foo.com". From the security perspective, to provide protection against possible Man-In-The-Middle attacks, we strongly recommend to use "strict" option. Default value\: strict Valid values\: strict, browser_compatible, allow_all trustKeystore - The pathname of the Java TrustStore file. This contains certificates from other parties that you expect to communicate with, or from Certificate Authorities that you trust to identify other parties. If the protocol (specified by the URL) is not HTTPS or if trustAllRoots is "true" this input is ignored. Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts Format\: Java KeyStore (JKS) trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file. If trustAllRoots is false and trustKeystore is empty, trustPassword default will be supplied. Default value\: changeit connectTimeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A timeout value of 0 represents an infinite timeout. Default value\: 0 Format\: an integer representing seconds Examples\: 10, 20 socketTimeout - The timeout for waiting for data (a maximum period inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A socketTimeout value of 0 represents an infinite timeout. Default value\: 0 Format\: an integer representing seconds useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls in a serializable session object therefore they will be available on a branch level (same subflow, same lane). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false keepAlive - Specifies whether to create a shared connection that will be used in subsequent calls. If keepAlive is false, the already open connection will be used and after execution it will close it. The operation will use a connection pool stored in a GlobalSessionObject that will be available throughout the execution (the flow and subflows, between parallel split lanes). Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false connectionsMaxPerRoute - The maximum limit of connections on a per route basis. The default will create no more than 2 concurrent connections per given route. Default value\: 2 connectionsMaxTotal - The maximum limit of connections in total. The default will create no more than 2 concurrent connections in total. Default value\: 20 headers - The list containing the headers to use for the request separated by new line (CRLF).The header name - value pair will be separated by "\:". Format\: According to HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616). Examples\: Accept\:text/plain responseCharacterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP response. If responseCharacterSet is empty, the charset from the 'Content-Type' HTTP response header will be used. If responseCharacterSet is empty and the charset from the HTTP response Content-Type header is empty, the default value will be used. You should not use this for method\=HEAD or OPTIONS. Default value\: ISO-8859-1 followRedirects - Specifies whether the HTTP client automatically follows redirects. Redirects explicitly prohibited by the HTTP specification as requiring user intervention will not be followed (redirects on POST and PUT requests that are converted to GET requests). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false requestCharacterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP request body. If contentType is empty, the requestCharacterSet will use the default value. If contentType will include charset (ex.\: "application/json; charset\=UTF-8"), the requestCharacterSet value will overwrite the charset value from contentType input. This should not be provided for method\=GET, HEAD, TRACE Default value\: ISO-8859-1 Results\: returnResult - This will contain the response entity. In case of an error this output will contain the error message. document - This will contain the response body. exception - In case of success response, this result is empty. In case of failure response, this result contains the java stack trace of the runtime exception. statusCode - The HTTP status code. Format\: 1xx (Informational - Request received, continuing process), 2xx (Success - The action was successfully received, understood, and accepted), 3xx (Redirection - Further action must be taken in order to complete the request), 4xx (Client Error - The request contains bad syntax or cannot be fulfilled), 5xx Server Error - The server failed to fulfil an apparently valid request) Examples\: 200, 404 responseHeaders - The list containing the headers of the response message, separated by newline. Format\: This is conforming with HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616). Responses success - The operation completed without a runtime exception. failure - A runtime exception occurred. This may be due to incorrectly formated inputs (headers, proxy, queryParams, url). Notes\: 1. The values stored in the fields of the Incident will not be changed if the "incident" inputs are left empty. 2. The reference of the "incident" inputs should be removed from inside the "requestBody" input when they are deleted. 3. When more Incident fields are required, than the ones exposed, you can add them as inputs and insert their reference in the Json found in the "requestBody" input. 4. In order to authenticate using an OAuth token\: 4.1. The headers input should contain the following header\: Authorization\:Bearer 4.2.
